ost, prepares the peril of his enemy's son and the triumph of his own offspring. No, the 'judgments' were not so accidental, the 'slaughters' not so casual as they seemed to Horatio the Recorder, and there is a note of deep satisfaction (which the audience cannot help sharing) in the young hero's guttural exclamation — Ha-ha, this quarry cries on havoc (meaning: the foxes have devoured one another) — as he surveys the rich heap of dead bodies, all that is left of the rotten state of Denmark.